article.headline: Top-ranked Duke doesn't panic, and does win

images.name: Lewis India 021130 inline

article.linkText: Beard's FTs finally lift No. 1 Duke past No. 15 Arkansas
article.story:
CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) -- Top-ranked Duke
expected to have a tough time with Arkansas (No. 15 ESPN/USA Today; No. 17 Associated Press).

<photo1>

	   The Blue Devils got just what they bargained for -- maybe more.

	   Alana Beard made two free throws with one second left in
overtime to complete a 27-point performance, and Duke escaped with
a 74-72 victory Saturday.

	   ''We learned a lot about ourselves,'' Dukes coach Gail
Goestenkors said. ''We got down and did not panic. We never lost
our poise.''

	   The victory gave Duke (5-0) the championship of the St. John
division of the Paradise Jam. Arkansas (4-1), which got 19 points
from Shameka Christon, had a chance to tie the game, but Lakisha
Harper's desperation shot hit the backboard and rim and bounced
away as time expired.

	   Arkansas had a 61-59 lead with 2:51 left in
regulation. But Mistie Bass made a layup to tie the score. Beard
had two chances to win the game in regulation, but missed from the
foul line with 17 seconds left and again with 11 remaining.

	   ''I know that free-throw shooting is one of my weaknesses, but I
am working on that,'' said Beard, the tournament most valuable player.

	   Iciss Tillis and Bass had 13 points apiece for the Blue Devils,
and Tillis pulled down 10 rebounds.

	   India Lewis added 15 points for the Lady Razorbacks, who also
got 14 from Dana Cherry and 11 from Rochelle Vaughn.

	   ''We played a great game,'' Arkansas coach Gary Blair said. ''We
have all the respect for Duke, but we are not intimidated by them.''
